\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7626777 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid476072\charrsid10379359 Did the teachers concern themselves at all about ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11083444 HO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid476072\charrsid10379359 
Yes, they - I - I think they taught us very well really, they - they - wouldn't - we hadn't to do a lot of talking you know and they - I can remember when I went to the higher class the schoolmaster, we had to co
me on - go on a lane by the mill and - the headmaster, he - he came the other way and we were going this way and he - and we used to run as fast as ever we possibly could to say good morning sir. That's only man I can remember calling sir. And he used to 
raise his hat to us and we thought it were wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7626777 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid476072\charrsid10379359 Was this when you were in the big school?
